\title{Moduli of Brain States}
\taxon{bridge}
\author{monaduck1069}
\date{2026-03-30}
\tag{cross-reference}
\tag{bci}
\tag{moduli}

\p{A moduli problem: classify brain states up to gauge equivalence (re-referencing). The Stacks Project provides the full machinery.}

\p{\strong{The moduli stack #{\mathcal{M}_{\mathrm{brain}}}:}}
\ul{
  \li{Objects: pairs #{(M, \sigma)} where #{M} is a montage (site) and #{\sigma} is a global section of the signal sheaf.}
  \li{Morphisms: gauge transformations (re-referencing maps) that preserve signal content.}
  \li{The stack quotient #{[\mathrm{Signals}/\mathrm{Gauge}]} parametrizes gauge-equivalence classes.}
}

\p{\strong{Stacks Project chapters}:}
\ul{
  \li{[[stk-0108]] \strong{Moduli Stacks} --- General theory of moduli problems as algebraic stacks. Obstruction theory, deformation theory, and representability.}
  \li{[[stk-0094]] \strong{Algebraic Stacks} --- #{\mathcal{M}_{\mathrm{brain}}} is an algebraic stack if Artin's axioms are satisfied. The key axiom: the diagonal is representable.}
  \li{[[stk-0090]] \strong{Formal Deformation Theory} --- Small perturbations of brain state (e.g., noise, drift) are formal deformations. The cotangent complex ([[stk-0092]]) controls the deformation theory.}
  \li{[[stk-0099]] \strong{Quot and Hilbert Spaces} --- The space of subsignals (e.g., alpha-band extraction) is a Quot scheme.}
  \li{[[stk-0109]] \strong{Moduli of Curves} --- Analogy: brain signals are curves in spectral space. The moduli space #{\overline{M}_{g,n}} has a BCI analogue where genus = complexity and marked points = electrode positions.}
}

\p{The BCI Factory's proof-of-human protocol ([[bcf-0005]]) is a point on #{\mathcal{M}_{\mathrm{brain}}} --- a certified brain state, witnessed by the community.}
